  "prompt": "Is there such a thing as an agnostic theist?",
  "response": "Yes, an agnostic theist is a real philosophical position. This term describes someone who believes in the existence of a god or gods (theist) but also believes that the nature or existence of god is ultimately unknowable or uncertain (agnostic).\n\nIn other words, an agnostic theist:\n1. Believes in the existence of a divine being\n2. Acknowledges that they cannot definitively prove or fully understand the nature of that divine being\n\nThis is different from:\n- Gnostic theists (who believe in god and claim to know god's nature with certainty)\n- Agnostic atheists (who do not believe in god and think god's existence is unknowable)\n- Gnostic atheists (who believe no god exists and claim to know this with certainty)\n\nAn agnostic theist might say something like, \"I believe in God, but I recognize that I can't fully comprehend or prove God's existence.\"",
